Total predictions = 10
Correct predictions = 9
Accuracy = 9/10 = 90%

3. When Accuracy Works Well

Accuracy is great when the dataset has a balanced number of classes.
Example: 50% pass, 50% fail → accuracy gives a fair measure.

4. Limitation of Accuracy

Accuracy can be misleading if the dataset is imbalanced.

Example:

Suppose 95 students fail, and only 5 students pass.
A silly model that always predicts Fail (0) would still get 95/100 correct → 95% accuracy.
But it completely fails to identify students who pass!

